subSubSection.paragraph:
Ciliation: Three sensory hairs (L 7-15 
µm
) project forward on either side of the mouth and others (L 10-20 
µm
) project obliquely from the head; a broad band of cephalic cilia (L 15-20 
µm
) covers the head and joins the locomotor ciliature ventrally; 18-20 sensory hairs each occur regularly in lateral (L 4-6 
µm
), dorsolateral (L 10-14 
µm
) and dorsal (L 14-20 
µm
) columns along each side of the trunk. Ventral locomotor ciliature forms two longitudinal bands of short (L 4-6 
µm
), scattered cilia that follow the lateral body contours the entire length of the body, separate medially beneath the head and pharynx, but converging behind the anus and merging into a single band onto the caudum.

Saegailus (Greek: sos + aigialos = meaning 'safe 
shore'
) refers to its shallow sublittoral habitat along the southern Mediterranean being sheltered from the west wind (zephyr).
